    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that's helpful, thanks. what about other things that cause browning? like caramelization? is that the same thing as the Maillard reaction or is it different? i just wanna make sure i dont mix them up on the test.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "No problem! Caramelization is indeed a browning process, but it's different from the Maillard reaction. Caramelization occurs when sugars break down and form new compounds without the need for amino acids, typically starting around 160°C (320°F). It's like when you make caramel sauce or toast a marshmallow. The Maillard reaction, on the other hand, requires both amino acids and reducing sugars, as I mentioned before. So, while both processes contribute to browning and flavor, they're like different paths in a magical forest, each with its own unique journey and destination. Good luck with your exam!",
      "source": "target",
